ðŸ”¹ Task-1: Create a Simple Jenkins Freestyle Job

ðŸ”¸ Objective

To verify Jenkins job execution by running a simple shell command.

ðŸ”¸ Step-by-Step Procedure Step 1: Start Jenkins

Open browser and access Jenkins:

http://localhost:8080

Login using Jenkins admin credentials.

Step 2: Create a Freestyle Job

    Click New Item

Enter job name:

Hello-Jenkins-Job

    Select Freestyle project

    Click OK

Step 3: Add Build Step

1.Scroll to Build

2.Click Add build step

3.Select Execute shell

Enter the command:

echo "Hello Jenkins"

Step 4: Save and Build

    Click Save

    Click Build Now

    Open Console Output

ðŸ”¸ Output

Hello Jenkins
Finished: SUCCESS

ðŸ”¸ Result

The Jenkins Freestyle job executed successfully.

ðŸ”¹ Task-2: Jenkins with GitHub Integration

ðŸ”¸ Objective

To configure Jenkins to clone a GitHub repository using a Freestyle job.

ðŸ”¸ Step-by-Step Procedure Step 1: Create GitHub Repository

    Login to GitHub

    Create a public repository

    jenkins-demo

Step 2: Clone Repository Locally

git clone https://github.com/<username>/jenkins-demo.git
cd jenkins-demo

Step 3: Add Sample Code

echo "Hello Jenkins GitHub Integration" > index.html
git add index.html
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git push origin main

Step 4: Verify Git Installation

git --version

If not installed:

sudo apt update
sudo apt install git -y

Step 5: Configure Git in Jenkins

Jenkins Dashboard â†’ Manage Jenkins

Click Global Tool Configuration

Under Git:

Name: Default-Git

Path:

/usr/bin/git

Click Save

Step 6: Create Jenkins Job

Click New Item

Job name:

GitHub-Clone-Job

Select Freestyle project

Click OK

Step 7: Configure Source Code Management

Scroll to Source Code Management

Select Git

Enter:

Repository URL: https://github.com/<username>/jenkins-demo.git
Branch: */main

Leave credentials empty (public repo)

Step 8: Build and Verify

    Click Save

    Click Build Now

    Open Console Output

ðŸ”¸ Output

Cloning the remote Git repository
Checking out Revision
Finished: SUCCESS

ðŸ”¸ Result

Jenkins successfully cloned the GitHub repository.

ðŸ”¹ Task-3: Automated Build using Poll SCM

ðŸ”¸ Objective

To automate Jenkins build execution when source code changes.

ðŸ”¸ Step-by-Step Procedure Step 1: Create GitHub Repository

Create a public repository:

jenkins-build-demo

Step 2: Clone Repository

git clone https://github.com/<username>/jenkins-build-demo.git
cd jenkins-build-demo

Step 3: Add Build File

echo "Automated Jenkins Build" > build.txt
git add build.txt
git commit -m "Initial build file"
git push origin main

Step 4: Create Jenkins Job

    Jenkins Dashboard â†’ New Item

Job name:

Automated-Build-Job

    Select Freestyle project

    Click OK

Step 5: Configure Git SCM

Repository URL:

https://github.com/<username>/jenkins-build-demo.git

Branch:

*/main

Step 6: Enable Poll SCM

    Scroll to Build Triggers

    Enable Poll SCM

Enter schedule:

H/2 * * * *

Step 7: Add Build Steps

Scroll to Build

Add Execute shell

Enter:

echo "Build started"
date
echo "Files in workspace:"
ls
echo "Build completed"

Step 8: Save and Run Initial Build

    Click Save

    Click Build Now

    Verify build success

Step 9: Trigger Automated Build

Modify file:

echo "Triggering automated build" >> build.txt
git add build.txt
git commit -m "Trigger build"
git push origin main

Wait 2 minutes.

ðŸ”¸ Output

Jenkins automatically triggers a new build

Console output:

Build started
Build completed
Finished: SUCCESS

ðŸ”¸ Result

Jenkins automatically detected source code changes and executed the build successfully.

ðŸ”¹ Final Conclusion

This experiment demonstrated Jenkins Freestyle jobs, GitHub integration, and automated build triggering using SCM polling, validating the Continuous Integration workflow.
